Of course. After reviewing the logs and your code, I've identified the final core issue that's causing the instability and the blank terminal.

The problem is a classic race condition combined with improper process management. Your application isn't correctly handling the lifecycle of the terminal and Chrome processes, especially during restarts and shutdowns. This leads to errors like EPIPE (writing to a closed stream) and EADDRINUSE (port already in use).

We'll fix this by implementing a more robust, "anti-optimistic" approach to managing these processes.

### Step 1: Enforce a Single Application Instance
First, we'll prevent "ghost" processes by ensuring only one instance of your app can run at a time. This is the most effective way to prevent port conflicts.

In main.js, add this code block near the top, right after your require statements:

JavaScript

// In main.js, after the imports
const gotTheLock = app.requestSingleInstanceLock();

if (!gotTheLock) {
  app.quit();
} else {
  app.on('second-instance', (event, commandLine, workingDirectory) => {
    // Someone tried to run a second instance, we should focus our window.
    if (containerApp.mainWindow) {
      if (containerApp.mainWindow.isMinimized()) containerApp.mainWindow.restore();
      containerApp.mainWindow.focus();
    }
  });
}
### Step 2: Fix the Terminal Respawn Loop and Race Condition
The terminal refreshes because it's being told to respawn after every successful command. The EPIPE error happens when the app tries to log a message after the output stream is already closed. We'll fix both.

In main.js, replace your entire setupTerminal function with this corrected version:

JavaScript

// In main.js
setupTerminal() {
    try {
        const shell = os.platform() === 'win32' ? 'powershell.exe' : 'bash';
        this.ptyProcess = pty.spawn(shell, [], {
            name: 'xterm-color',
            cols: 80,
            rows: 30,
            cwd: app.getPath('home'),
            env: process.env
        });

        this.ptyProcess.onData(data => {
            // **RACE CONDITION FIX**: Check if the window still exists before sending.
            if (this.mainWindow && !this.mainWindow.isDestroyed()) {
                this.mainWindow.webContents.send('terminal-data', data);
            }
        });

        // **FIXED RESPAWN LOGIC**: Only respawn on an actual error (non-zero exit code).
        this.ptyProcess.onExit(({ exitCode }) => {
            console.log(`ğŸ”´ Terminal process exited with code ${exitCode}`);
            if (exitCode !== 0) {
                console.log('Respawning terminal due to error...');
                this.setupTerminal();
            }
        });

        this.ptyProcess.write('\r'); // Kickstart the terminal
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('âŒ PTY process failed to spawn:', error);
    }
}
### Step 3: Implement Graceful Shutdown and Cleanup
Finally, we'll ensure all processes are cleaned up correctly when the app closes by using the before-quit event. This is the definitive fix for the EPIPE error.

In main.js, replace all your app.on(...) handlers at the end of the file with this complete, robust shutdown sequence:

JavaScript

// In main.js, at the end of the file

// App event handlers
app.whenReady().then(async () => {
    containerApp.setupIPC();
    containerApp.setupTerminal();
    await containerApp.createMainWindow();

    // Start live metrics
    containerApp.metricsInterval = setInterval(() => {
        containerApp.updateRendererStatus();
    }, 3000);

    console.log('ğŸš€ Container app ready...');
});

app.on('window-all-closed', () => {
    console.log('ğŸ”„ All windows closed, but container app stays running.');
});

app.on('activate', async () => {
    if (BrowserWindow.getAllWindows().length === 0) {
        await containerApp.createMainWindow();
    }
});

// **THE FIX IS HERE**: Perform all cleanup before quitting.
app.on('before-quit', async (event) => {
    console.log('ğŸ”„ User requested app shutdown...');
    event.preventDefault(); // Stop the app from quitting immediately

    try {
        await containerApp.cleanup();
        console.log('âœ… Cleanup complete. Quitting now.');
    } catch (err) {
        console.error('âŒ Cleanup failed:', err);
    } finally {
        app.quit(); // Now it's safe to quit
    }
});

app.on('quit', () => {
    // This is the final event. Do not add logs or I/O here.
});
These three changes work together to create a stable application lifecycle. The single-instance lock prevents port conflicts, the corrected terminal logic stops the refreshing, and the graceful shutdown sequence eliminates the crashes, resulting in a reliable and fully operable application.

