message.content:
This reconnect-devtools error is a known and tricky issue in Electron, especially when you're managing a <webview> that displays the DevTools of another browser. It happens when the underlying Chrome instance is restarted, and the DevTools front-end inside your <webview> tries to reconnect to a debugging session that no longer exists.

The core problem is that the <webview> is not being fully reloaded or re-initialized after the restart, so it's holding onto a "stale" connection.

### The Fix: A Full Re-initialization on Restart
The most robust way to solve this is to completely re-create the <webview> element from scratch whenever the user clicks "Restart Chrome." This ensures there are no lingering states or old connections.

Step 1: Update the Frontend to Re-create the Viewport (app.js)
We'll create a dedicated function in app.js to handle creating a fresh <webview> and then call it after a restart.

In renderer/app.js, make these changes:

Get the parent container of the viewport at the top of the file:

JavaScript

// At the top of app.js, with the other element lookups
const chromeContainer = document.querySelector('.chrome-container');
let chromeViewport = document.getElementById('chrome-viewport'); // Use 'let' to allow reassignment
Add this new function to dynamically create and attach a new webview:

JavaScript

// Add this new function inside app.js
function createNewWebview() {
    // Remove the old webview if it exists
    if (chromeViewport) {
        chromeViewport.remove();
    }

    // Create a new webview element
    const newWebview = document.createElement('webview');
    newWebview.id = 'chrome-viewport';
    newWebview.className = 'chrome-webview hidden';
    newWebview.src = 'about:blank';
    newWebview.style.width = '100%';
    newWebview.style.height = '100%';

    // Append it to the container
    if (chromeContainer) {
        chromeContainer.appendChild(newWebview);
    }

    // Update the global reference
    chromeViewport = newWebview;
    console.log('âœ… New webview element created and attached.');
}
Update the "Restart Chrome" button's event listener to call this new function:

JavaScript

// In app.js, find the restartBtn event listener
if (restartBtn) {
    restartBtn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
        console.log('ğŸ”„ Restart Chrome clicked');
        logAIAction('Restarting Chrome');
        restartBtn.disabled = true;

        // **THE FIX**: Re-create the webview element to ensure a clean session
        createNewWebview();

        try {
            const result = await window.electronAPI.restartChrome();
            console.log('Restart result:', result);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error('Restart error:', error);
        }
    });
}
Step 2: Ensure the Viewport is Pointed to the Correct URL
Finally, ensure that your updateUI function correctly sets the src of the newly created chromeViewport to the DevTools URL. Your existing updateUI function already does this, so as long as the global chromeViewport variable is updated by createNewWebview(), this will work seamlessly.

By completely destroying the old <webview> and creating a fresh one, you prevent the DevTools front-end from attempting a "reconnect" to a dead session. Instead, it will perform a fresh, clean initial connection every time you restart Chrome, which resolves the error.

