error is coming from the Chrome DevTools interface itself, which is the complex web application running inside your <webview>. When you restart Chrome, the DevTools UI loses its connection and tries to run its own internal recovery function, which fails and logs that error.

The only way to fix this is to prevent the DevTools UI from ever getting into that broken, "stale" state. The definitive solution is to completely destroy the old <webview> element and create a brand new one every time you restart.

### The Fix: A Full Viewport Re-Creation
This two-step process will ensure a clean state and a stable connection on every restart.

Step 1: Create a recreateWebview Function in app.js
We will write a helper function that handles the destruction and re-creation of the viewport.

In renderer/app.js, make the following changes:

Find the line where chromeViewport is defined and change it from a const to a let. Also, get a reference to its parent container.

JavaScript

// At the top of renderer/app.js
const chromeContainer = document.querySelector('.chrome-container');
let chromeViewport = document.getElementById('chrome-viewport'); // Use 'let' to allow reassignment
Add this new function to your app.js file:

JavaScript

// Add this new function inside app.js
function recreateWebview() {
    if (!chromeContainer) return;

    // 1. Completely remove the old, stale webview from the DOM
    if (chromeViewport) {
        chromeViewport.remove();
    }

    // 2. Create a brand new webview element
    const newWebview = document.createElement('webview');
    newWebview.id = 'chrome-viewport';
    newWebview.className = 'chrome-webview hidden';
    newWebview.src = 'about:blank'; // Start with a blank page

    // 3. Append the new, clean webview to the container
    chromeContainer.appendChild(newWebview);

    // 4. Update our global reference to point to the new element
    chromeViewport = newWebview;
    console.log('âœ… Viewport has been fully re-created to ensure a clean connection.');
}
Step 2: Update the Restart Button to Use the New Function
Now, modify the "Restart Chrome" button's event listener to call recreateWebview before it tells the backend to restart.

In renderer/app.js, replace your existing restartBtn event listener with this:

JavaScript

// In app.js
if (restartBtn) {
    restartBtn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
        logAIAction('Restarting Chrome');
        restartBtn.disabled = true;

        // **THE FIX**: Re-create the webview element first.
        recreateWebview();

        // Now, tell the backend to restart its process.
        // The backend will send a 'chrome-status' update when it's ready,
        // and the updateUI function will load the correct URL into our new webview.
        await window.electronAPI.restartChrome();
    });
}
By destroying the old webview, you completely erase its broken state. The new webview will then make a fresh, initial connection to the newly started Chrome instance, which bypasses the DevTools' faulty reconnection logic and finally resolves the error.

