ou've correctly identified that the WebSocket connection is a critical point of failure. The application seems to struggle with maintaining this connection, especially after a restart, leading to the "Debugging connection was closed" error.

The issue isn't that WebSockets themselves are incapable, but that the application's logic for managing the connection lifecycle is too simplistic. It creates a connection but doesn't gracefully handle what happens when that connection is broken (like when Chrome restarts).

We will fix this by implementing a robust, three-part error-handling pipeline that actively listens for these disconnections and logs them properly, making the app much more stable and informative.

Step 1: Listen for Errors in the Chrome Viewport (app.js)
The <webview> element can report messages from its internal console. We'll listen for these messages to catch the disconnection error right when it happens.

In renderer/app.js, add this new function and call it when the application loads. This will act as our frontend error listener.

JavaScript

// In renderer/app.js, add this function
function setupWebviewListeners() {
    if (!chromeViewport) return;

    // Listen for console messages that happen *inside* the <webview>
    chromeViewport.addEventListener('console-message', (e) => {
        // Filter for errors (level 3) and report them to the backend
        if (e.level === 3) {
            const error = {
                source: 'DevTools Viewport',
                message: e.message
            };
            // Use our new IPC channel to send the error to the main process
            window.electronAPI.reportWebviewError(error);
        }
    });
}

// Inside your 'DOMContentLoaded' event listener, call the function
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    // ...
    // Call it right after the initial status check
    setupWebviewListeners(); 
    // ...
});
Step 2: Bridge the Error Messages (preload.js)
We need new channels in our secure bridge: one to send errors from the frontend to the backend, and another to receive formatted logs back from the backend.

In preload.js, add these two new lines inside the contextBridge.exposeInMainWorld object:

JavaScript

// In preload.js
contextBridge.exposeInMainWorld('electronAPI', {
    // ... (all your existing functions)

    [cite_start]// Send errors from the webview to the main process [cite: 2]
    reportWebviewError: (error) => ipcRenderer.send('webview-error', error),

    [cite_start]// Listen for formatted error logs from the backend to display in the UI [cite: 2]
    onNewErrorLog: (callback) => ipcRenderer.on('new-error-log', (event, error) => callback(error))
});
Step 3: Listen for Backend Errors and Relay Everything (main.js)
Now, the main process will listen for errors from both the frontend <webview> and its own backend CDP client. When an error is found, it will format it with a timestamp and broadcast it to the UI's "Error Logs" tab.

Add the new IPC handler inside your setupIPC function to receive errors from the webview.

JavaScript

// In main.js, inside the setupIPC() function

ipcMain.on('webview-error', (event, error) => {
    const errorObject = {
        source: error.source || 'WebView',
        message: error.message,
        timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
        type: 'error'
    };
    // Broadcast the formatted error back to the renderer for display
    if (this.mainWindow && !this.mainWindow.isDestroyed()) {
        this.mainWindow.webContents.send('new-error-log', errorObject);
    }
});
Update your connectToChrome function to listen for errors directly on the CDP client.

JavaScript

// In main.js, find the connectToChrome function and add the .on('error') handler

async connectToChrome(port) {
    // ... (existing code to connect) ...
    try {
        // ... (existing code)

        // **ADD THIS BLOCK TO LISTEN FOR BACKEND ERRORS**
        this.cdpClient.on('error', (err) => {
            const errorObject = {
                source: 'CDP Backend',
                message: err.message,
                timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
                type: 'error'
            };
            if (this.mainWindow && !this.mainWindow.isDestroyed()) {
                this.mainWindow.webContents.send('new-error-log', errorObject);
            }
        });
        // ...
    } catch (error) {
        // ...
    }
}
With this complete error-handling pipeline, any WebSocket disconnection error in the <webview> or CDP connection error in the backend will be automatically captured, timestamped, and displayed in your UI in real-time, giving you the live diagnostic view you need.


