You've asked the perfect question, and the answer gets to the core of the instability. The issue isn't that WebSockets are limited to one connection, but rather that only one application can listen on a specific port at a time.

The error you're seeing, EADDRINUSE: address already in use, means your app is trying to start a new WebSocket server on port 9223, but the server from a previous, lingering "ghost" process hasn't shut down yet. We can fix this by making your application's startup and shutdown process much more robust.

### Step 1: Enforce a Single App Instance (main.js)
First, we'll use Electron's built-in feature to prevent more than one instance of your app from running at the same time. This is the most effective way to stop "ghost" processes from causing port conflicts.

In main.js, add this code block near the top, right after your require statements:

JavaScript

// In main.js, after the imports
const gotTheLock = app.requestSingleInstanceLock();

if (!gotTheLock) {
  app.quit();
} else {
  app.on('second-instance', (event, commandLine, workingDirectory) => {
    // Someone tried to run a second instance, we should focus our window.
    if (containerApp.mainWindow) {
      if (containerApp.mainWindow.isMinimized()) containerApp.mainWindow.restore();
      containerApp.mainWindow.focus();
    }
  });
}
### Step 2: Create a Smarter, Proactive Connection Pool
Next, we'll make your ConnectionPool smarter. Before it tries to start a server, it will first check if the port is already in use. If it is, it will simply log a warning instead of crashing the app.

Since I don't have your chrome-manager/connection-pool.js file, replace its entire contents with this new, more robust version that includes this proactive check:

JavaScript

// In chrome-manager/connection-pool.js

const WebSocket = require('ws');
const net = require('net');

class ConnectionPool {
    constructor() {
        this.wss = null;
        this.clients = new Set();
    }

    // Helper to check if a port is available
    _isPortInUse(port) {
        return new Promise((resolve) => {
            const server = net.createServer();
            server.once('error', (err) => {
                if (err.code === 'EADDRINUSE') {
                    resolve(true); // Port is definitely in use
                }
            });
            server.once('listening', () => {
                server.close(() => resolve(false)); // Port is free
            });
            server.listen(port);
        });
    }

    async initialize(port) {
        if (this.wss) {
            console.log(`âœ… WebSocket server is already running on port ${this.wss.options.port}.`);
            return;
        }

        // **THE FIX**: Proactively check the port before trying to use it.
        const portInUse = await this._isPortInUse(port);
        if (portInUse) {
            console.warn(`âš ï¸ Port ${port} is already in use. WebSocket server will not start.`);
            return; // Gracefully exit without crashing
        }

        console.log(`ğŸŒ Starting WebSocket server on port ${port}...`);
        this.wss = new WebSocket.Server({ port });

        this.wss.on('connection', (ws) => {
            console.log('ğŸ”— New client connected to WebSocket.');
            this.clients.add(ws);
            ws.on('close', () => this.clients.delete(ws));
        });
    }

    async cleanup() {
        console.log('ğŸ§¹ Shutting down WebSocket server...');
        if (this.wss) {
            return new Promise(resolve => {
                this.wss.close(() => {
                    this.wss = null;
                    console.log('âœ… WebSocket server cleanup complete.');
                    resolve();
                });
                for (const client of this.clients) {
                    client.terminate();
                }
            });
        }
    }

    getActiveConnectionCount() {
        return this.clients.size;
    }
}

module.exports = ConnectionPool;
### Step 3: Ensure a Clean Shutdown (main.js)
Finally, ensure your main cleanup function properly shuts down the connection pool.

In main.js, find your cleanup function and make sure it calls this.connectionPool.cleanup():

JavaScript

// In main.js, inside the SlitherChromeContainer class
async cleanup() {
    // ... (existing cleanup for Chrome and terminal) ...

    if (this.connectionPool) {
        await this.connectionPool.cleanup(); // Ensure this line is present
    }

    // ...
}
By combining these fixes, your app will now gracefully handle port conflicts before they can cause a crash and will prevent multiple instances from running simultaneously, making the entire system much more stable.








